#include<iostream> 
using namespace std;
int main()
{
  int a =10, b=5;
  bool x =(a>b) ? true : false;
  cout<<x; 
  
  int y =(a>b) ? true : false;
  cout<<y;

}


//output 11


In C++, the bool type is a fundamental data type that can represent either true or false.
When you print a bool using cout, it is displayed as 1 for true and 0 for false. This is just a convention in C++.

So, when you print the value of x using cout, even though x is of type bool and has the value true, it will be displayed as 1:
